Part I — Space, Time, and Measurement

Chapter 1 — Fundamental Quantities

Physics begins with measurement. Before we can state laws, we must define what we measure. The universe presents five fundamental dimensions from which all others derive.

Length (L): The extension of an object in space. In human units, the meter (m). But the universe provides a natural length scale—the Planck length—below which space-time itself may cease to be meaningful.

Time (T): The dimension of change, of before and after. In human units, the second (s). The universe provides a natural time scale—the Planck time—the time for light to traverse a Planck length.

Mass (M): The measure of inertia, of resistance to acceleration. In human units, the kilogram (kg). The universe provides a natural mass scale—the Planck mass—where quantum gravity effects become significant.

Charge (Q): The source of electromagnetic force. In human units, the coulomb (C). Unlike mass, charge comes in discrete units—the elementary charge e.

Temperature (Θ): The measure of average kinetic energy in a system. In human units, the kelvin (K). At absolute zero, all classical motion ceases, though quantum fluctuations remain.

All other physical quantities are combinations of these five:

Quantity Dimensional Formula SI Unit
Velocity $L T^{-1}$ m/s
Acceleration $L T^{-2}$ m/s²
Force $M L T^{-2}$ newton (N)
Energy $M L^2 T^{-2}$ joule (J)
Power $M L^2 T^{-3}$ watt (W)
Pressure $M L^{-1} T^{-2}$ pascal (Pa)
Electric field $M L T^{-3} I^{-1}$ V/m
Magnetic field $M T^{-2} I^{-1}$ tesla (T)
Entropy $M L^2 T^{-2} \Theta^{-1}$ J/K

Natural Units

The SI system is anthropocentric—the meter is one ten-millionth of the distance from pole to equator, the kilogram is the mass of a liter of water. A universal physics requires universal units, based on fundamental constants:

l_P = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar G}{c^3}} \approx 1.616 \times 10^{-35} \text{ m}

t_P = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar G}{c^5}} \approx 5.391 \times 10^{-44} \text{ s}

m_P = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar c}{G}} \approx 2.176 \times 10^{-8} \text{ kg}

T_P = \frac{m_P c^2}{k_B} \approx 1.417 \times 10^{32} \text{ K}

At these scales, $c = \hbar = G = k_B = 1$, and the distinctions between quantum mechanics, relativity, and thermodynamics dissolve. This is the domain of quantum gravity—the final frontier.

