Chapter 154 — Matter-Antimatter Asymmetry

The universe is made almost entirely of matter. Why is there so little antimatter?

The Problem:
The Big Bang should have produced equal amounts of matter and antimatter. They would have annihilated, leaving only radiation. Yet we exist.

Sakharov Conditions (1967):
For baryogenesis (generation of matter excess), three conditions are necessary:

1. Baryon number violation: Processes that change $B$
2. C and CP violation: Different behavior of matter and antimatter
3. Out-of-equilibrium conditions: No time for reverse reactions

Standard Model CP Violation:
The CKM matrix provides some CP violation, but too little to explain the observed asymmetry.

Possible Mechanisms:

· Leptogenesis: Heavy right-handed neutrinos decay, creating lepton asymmetry, converted to baryon asymmetry by sphalerons
· Electroweak baryogenesis: First-order phase transition at electroweak scale
· Affleck-Dine mechanism: Scalar field dynamics in SUSY

Observational Tests: Neutrinoless double beta decay, proton decay searches, precision measurements of CP violation.

