Chapter 155 — The Hierarchy Problem

The Higgs boson mass is about 125 GeV. Quantum corrections would drive it to the Planck scale ($10^{19}$ GeV) unless something cancels them.

\Delta m_H^2 \sim \frac{\Lambda^2}{16\pi^2}

where $\Lambda$ is the cutoff scale. For $\Lambda = M_{\text{Planck}}$, the correction is enormous.

Fine-Tuning: The bare mass and quantum corrections must cancel to 1 part in $10^{32}$—unnaturally precise.

Proposed Solutions:

Supersymmetry:
Fermion and boson partners cancel divergences.

[Q, H] = 0, \quad Q|{\rm boson}\rangle = |{\rm fermion}\rangle

· Predicts superpartners for all particles
· No evidence at LHC so far

Extra Dimensions:
Gravity propagates in bulk, lowering the fundamental Planck scale.

M_{\text{Planck}}^2 \sim M_*^{n+2} R^n

· Large extra dimensions (ADD model)
· Warped extra dimensions (RS model)

Composite Higgs:
Higgs is not fundamental but a bound state of some new strong interaction.

Naturalness vs. Multiverse:
Perhaps there is no solution—the parameters are environmental, selected by anthropic considerations in a multiverse.

