Chapter 156 — The Nature of Neutrinos

Neutrinos are the lightest massive particles. They oscillate—change flavor—proving they have mass.

Oscillation Parameters:

Three mixing angles: $\theta_{12}$, $\theta_{23}$, $\theta_{13}$
Two mass-squared differences: $\Delta m^2_{21}$, $\Delta m^2_{32}$
One CP-violating phase: $\delta_{\text{CP}}$

Open Questions:

1. Absolute mass scale: Upper limit from cosmology: $\sum m_\nu < 0.12$ eV
2. Mass hierarchy: Normal ($m_1 < m_2 < m_3$) or inverted ($m_3 < m_1 < m_2$)?
3. Majorana or Dirac? Are neutrinos their own antiparticles?
4. Sterile neutrinos: Are there additional neutrino types that don't interact weakly?

