Chapter 157 — The Strong CP Problem

Quantum chromodynamics allows a term that violates CP symmetry:

\mathcal{L}_\theta = \frac{\theta g^2}{32\pi^2} G_{\mu\nu}^a \tilde{G}_a^{\mu\nu}

Such a term would give the neutron an electric dipole moment. Measurements show it is tiny:

d_n < 1.8 \times 10^{-26} \text{ e·cm}

This implies $\theta < 10^{-10}$—another fine-tuning.

The Peccei-Quinn Solution:
Introduce a new global symmetry $U(1)_{\text{PQ}}$ that is spontaneously broken. This predicts a new particle: the axion.

Axions would be produced in the early universe and could constitute dark matter.

Current Searches: ADMX, CAST, IAXO, and many others.

