Chapter 159 — The Origin of the Universe

The Big Bang happened. But what came before? What caused it?

The Initial Singularity: Classical general relativity predicts a singularity at $t=0$—infinite density and temperature. Quantum gravity should replace this with something else.

Quantum Cosmology:

· Hartle-Hawking no-boundary proposal: Universe has no boundary in time; the wavefunction of the universe is a path integral over compact Euclidean geometries.
  \Psi[h_{ij}] = \int \mathcal{D}g e^{-S_{\text{E}}[g]}
· Tunneling proposal: Universe tunnels from nothing
· Bounce models: Universe contracts, then expands (loop quantum cosmology)

Inflation: Explains homogeneity, flatness, and structure, but requires its own initial conditions.

The Multiverse: Inflation may be eternal, producing countless bubble universes with different properties.

Testability: Cosmic microwave background polarization (B-modes) may probe inflation; quantum gravity effects might be observable in principle but extremely difficult.

